Ch 22 Text Mining

Exercises

Project Gutenberg is a digital archive of public domain books. The R package gutenbergr facilitates the importation of these texts into R.

You can install and load it like this:

install.packages("gutenbergr")
library(gutenbergr)

You can see the books that are available like this:

gutenberg_metadata

  1. Use str_detect to find the ID of the novel Pride and Prejudice.

Since the numeration in the gutenberg data starts with zero, we need to decrease the indexes by one. Here, I use the function str_which that combines the commands str_detect and which.

idx <- gutenberg_metadata %>% .$title %>% str_which("Pride and Prejudice") %>% .[]-1

In total we get 6 hits for the book “Pride and Prejudice”.

gutenberg_metadata %>% filter(gutenberg_id %in% idx)
  1. We notice that there are several versions. The gutenberg_works() function filters this table to remove replicates and include only English language works. Read the help file and use this function to find the ID for Pride and Prejudice

After removing the duplicates we end up with just two titles.

gutenberg_works() %>% filter(gutenberg_id %in% idx)

  1. Use the tidytext package to create a tidy table with all the words in the text.
library(tidytext)
book_tok <-book %>% unnest_tokens(word, text)
book_tok
  1. We will later make a plot of sentiment versus location in the book. For this, it will be useful to add a column with the word number to the table.
book_tok <- book_tok %>% mutate(word_number = row_number())
  1. Remove the stop words and numbers from the words object. Hint: use the anti_join.
words_df <- tbl_df(words)
names(words_df) <- "word"
